{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631164"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:23:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:23:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17351"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17351"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.8,0,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10041"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70622"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10041"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56087"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10024"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23512"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23710"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70622"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFat digestion in the small intestine requires several coordinated processes to break down dietary lipids into absorbable components. Bile salts play a role in this process.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of bile salts this process?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activation of pancreatic lipase","Direct break down of triglycerides","Emulsification of fats into smaller droplets","Stimulation of pancreatic enzyme secretion","Transportation of fatty acids into enterocytes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of bile salts is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eemulsify fats into smaller droplets\u003C/strong\u003E. This process increases the surface area of fat droplets, making them more accessible to lipase enzymes. Bile salts are amphipathic molecules that can interact with both water and fat, allowing them to break large fat droplets into smaller ones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly break down triglycerides\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of lipase enzymes, not bile salts\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulate pancreatic enzyme secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily regulated by cholecystokinin and secretin\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport fatty acids into enterocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - While bile salts help form micelles that assist fat absorption, they do not directly transport fatty acids\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivate pancreatic lipase\u003C/strong\u003E - Colipase, not bile salts, is responsible for lipase activation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter emulsification, the increased surface area allows pancreatic lipase to more efficiently hydrolyse triglycerides into fatty acids and monoglycerides. These products are then incorporated into micelles for absorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bile salts emulsify dietary fats by breaking large fat droplets into smaller ones, increasing surface area for lipase action.","Bile salts are amphipathic molecules that form micelles, which aid in fat absorption across the small intestine.","Fat emulsification is essential for efficient digestion as lipases can only act at the surface of fat droplets."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56087"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17351"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56087"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T10:53:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T10:54:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10041"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70622"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":nu